#elbow method to determine value of k
#create dictionary for wcss to plot
wcss = {}
for i in range(1, 11):
    kmeans = KMeans(n_clusters = i,n_init = 'auto', init='k-means++', random_state = 42)
    kmeans.fit(X)
    wcss[i] = kmeans.inertia_
plt.plot(wcss.keys(), wcss.values(), 'gs-')
plt.xlabel("Values of K")
plt.ylabel('WCSS')
plt.title('WCSS elbow method')
plt.show()

#parameter tuning with PCA (Principal Component Analysis) to transform high dimension data to lower dimension to interpret 
#and visualize data from several variables above to 2 variables
from sklearn.decomposition import PCA
for i in range(2, 10):
    kmeans = KMeans(n_clusters=i, n_init='auto', max_iter=100, init= "k-means++")
    kmeans.fit(X)
    pca=PCA(n_components=2)
    reduced_X=pd.DataFrame(data=pca.fit_transform(X),columns=['PCA1','PCA2'])
    #reduced features
    centers=pca.transform(kmeans.cluster_centers_)
    plt.figure(figsize=(7,5))
    plt.scatter(reduced_X['PCA1'],reduced_X['PCA2'],c=kmeans.labels_)
    plt.scatter(centers[:,0],centers[:,1],marker='o', s=100,c='blue')
    plt.xlabel('PCA1')
    plt.ylabel('PCA2')
    plt.title('Wine Cluster for cluster: {}'.format(i))
    plt.tight_layout()

In [329]:
euclidean = []
manhattan = []
cosine = []
from sklearn.metrics import silhouette_score
for i in range(2, 10):
    kmeans = KMeans(n_clusters=i, n_init='auto', max_iter=100, init= "k-means++")
    kmeans.fit(X)
    euclidean.append(silhouette_score(X, kmeans.labels_, metric='euclidean'))
    manhattan.append(silhouette_score(X, kmeans.labels_, metric='manhattan'))
    cosine.append(silhouette_score(X, kmeans.labels_, metric='cosine'))
